heories and Practices -- tThe Rest was not Perfected: Platonic Endings and their Modern Echoes -- tWar as a Permanent Civil War: The “Unfinished” History in Pasolini’s Petrolio -- tPart V: Searching for Completion -- tThe Missing Conclusion to Valerius Flaccus’ Argonautica -- tSpeaking Silences: The Incompleteness of Tacitus’ Annals and Gustav Freytag’s Die verlorene Handschrift -- tPutting an Unfinished Novel Back into Motion: A Digital Tool to Create Possible “Second Volumes” of Bouvard et Pécuchet -- tList of Contributors -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex of Passages0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnfinishedness and incompleteness are a central feature of ancient Greek and Roman literature that has often been taken for granted but not deeply examined; many texts have been transmitted to us incomplete. How and to what extent has this feature of many texts influenced their aesthetic perception and interpretation, and how does it still influence them today? Also, how do various editorial arrangements of fragmentary texts influence the reconstruction of closure? These important questions offer the opportunity to bring together specialists working on Greek and Roman texts across various genres: epic, tragedy, poetry, mythographic texts, rhetorical texts, philosophical treatises, and the novel. Reading a text by focusing on its current unfinishedness or incompleteness, or the textual signs suggesting an unfinished or incomplete state, the contributors examine the relations between author, reader and text as underscored by the verbal, generic and aesthetic features of each work. This edited volume brings together a broad spectrum of approaches to ancient and modern texts and aims to reach out to a broad scholarly community consisting not only of Classicists but also scholars of other literature and aesthetics.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn 